<opener><dateline><date>24 May 1916</date></dateline>
<salute>My dear Madam</salute></opener>
<p>I have received your
<lb/> letter of the 23 May.</p>
<p>Your description of the
<lb/> treatment endured by the
<lb/> prisoners in Richmond
<lb/> Barracks is very horrible.
<lb/>And your account is I
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="1734" facs="#L1916_706_img_1734"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>very much regret to say -
<lb/> confirmed by <hi rend="underline">many</hi> other
<lb/> accounts which have reached
<lb/> me.</p>
<p>Very strong representations
<lb/> have been made to the
<lb/> Government by myself and
<lb/> my colleagues in these
<lb/> matters &#x2014; And I understand that the
        
    
         
        <pb n="1735" facs="#L1916_706_img_1735"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>treatment at Richmond
<lb/> and other Dublin
<lb/> Barracks &#x2014; has within
<lb/> the last few days been
<lb/> very greatly improved.</p>
<p>Please find out
<lb/> how this matter now
<lb/> stands &amp; I shall
<lb/> attend immediately
<lb/> to any points which are
        
    
         
        <pb n="1736" facs="#L1916_706_img_1736"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>still matters of complaint.
<lb/> I shall keep in mind
<lb/> your husband's case &#x2014;
<lb/> And later on I may
<lb/> be able to do something
 to <del>null</del> mitigate the
<lb/> harshness of his sentence.</p>
<closer><salute>Yours Sincerely</salute>
<signed><hi rend="underline">John Dillon</hi></signed></closer>
        
    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        
            
        
            
        
            
        

         

